[As part of the upscale push, Kidder is putting brokers through a
20-week training course,]112 [turning them into "investment
counselors" with knowledge of corporate finance.]113 [They will get
"new and improved tools]114 [to sell, particularly to the affluent
investor,"]115 [says brokerage chief Charles V. Sheehan.]116

[Theoretically, the brokers will then be able to funnel "leads" on
corporate finance opportunities to Kidder's investment bankers,]117
[possibly easing the longstanding tension between the two camps.]118
[However, skeptics caution]119 [that this kind of cross-pollination
between brokers and investment bankers looks great on paper,]120 [but
doesn't always happen.]121

[Kidder competitors aren't outwardly hostile to the firm,]122 [as many
are to a tough competitor like Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.]123 [that
doesn't have Kidder's long history.]124 [However, competitors say]125
[that Kidder's hiring binge]126 [involving executive-level staffers,
some with multiple-year contract guarantees,]127 [could backfire]128
[unless there are results.]129

[The departing Mr. Cathcart says]130 [he has no worries about Kidder's
future.]131 [Mr. Cathcart,]132 [who will return to the Quaker Oats
Co. board of directors,]133 [in addition to his personal ventures, is
